US northeast experiences fresh bout of energy inflation due to higher home heating fuel costs

October core CPI finally came in under consensus, reversing months in which inflation exceeded market expectations. Aggressive Fed rate hikes and quantitative tightening are finally starting to take hold. Nonetheless, there remain pockets of inflationary concern. CPI for household fuels and utilities in the northeast accelerated 1.63% m/m, the inverse of a 0.87% m/m decline for the US in total. This was driven by sizeable increases in the cost for home heating fuels. US CPI on fuel oil, a subcategory of household energy, accelerated 19.8% m/m, the second largest increase going back a decade in time, a notable development given the bulk of residential heating fuels are consumed in the northeast. Lagging imports, a cut in refinery capacity and depleted diesel inventories are all to blame. It is likely that the northeast faces stickier energy inflation issues over the next several months relative to other regions in the United States. The Fed will need to be careful when implementing monetary policy to account for these regional differences.
